SIMPLE: hurry
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hurry
<hw>Hur"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hurried</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hurrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>horien</ets>; cf. OSw.
<ets>hurra</ets> to whirl round, dial. Sw. <ets>hurr</ets> great haste,
Dan. <ets>hurre</ets> to buzz, Icel. <ets>hurr</ets> hurly-burly, MHG.
<ets>hurren</ets> to hurry, and E. <ets>hurr</ets>, <ets>whir</ets> to
hurry; all prob. of imitative origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hasten;
to impel to greater speed; to urge on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Impetuous lust <qex>hurries</qex> him on.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>hurried</qex> him abroad a bark.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To impel to precipitate or thoughtless action; to
urge to confused or irregular activity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And wild amazement <qex>hurries</qex> up and down⟦br⟧
The little number of your doubtful friends.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to be done quickly.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To hasten; precipitate; expedite; quicken;
accelerate; urge.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hurry
<hw>Hur"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To move or act with haste; to
proceed with celerity or precipitation; <as>as, let us
<ex>hurry</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hurry up</b></col>, <cd>to make haste.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hurry
<hw>Hur"ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of hurrying in motion or
business; pressure; urgency; bustle; confusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ambition raises a tumult in the soul, it inflames the mind, and
puts into a violent <qex>hurry</qex> of thought.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Haste; speed; dispatch. See
<er>Haste</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurryingly</ent>⟦br⟧
